          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Utility- What is it?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.67)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=8900'>Chris "Fire83" Neathery</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=8900&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 13, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">        A deck is only as good as what you put in it and there is something that sets every deck apart. It separates every archetype, every copy. This single card type is in every tournament winning deck and in the best of the best. What&#8217;s the secret? What do these decks and players have that others don&#8217;t? <br>
       Utility. This type of card classification is what set apart every great deck from every other. <br>
       What is utility? Simply, utility is a card that is good in most situations and leaves open a valuable option. Utility also has the ability to be used in almost every deck. <br>
       How Do I know if something is utility? Most cards that are true utility cards are low in cost and most often spells or universal relics. Warrior&#8217;s Boots and Rayje&#8217;s Belt are two examples of utility relics. They are low in cost, zero in cost, and perform amazingly in almost every situation. In fact most of Rayje&#8217;s relics can be utility. Each cost very little and they have amazing abilities. The best sign for a relic that is utility is its ability to be widely used and a versatile power that can turn the tide of a game.<br>
       Spells are often more difficult to tell if they are utility. They are also more difficult to input a direct strategy out side of their region but only in the tightest of situations. These spells still earn the title of utility because they win games and turn the tides of a match. Each does what it does because it is efficient. Shockwave, Undertow, Thunderquake, and Storm of Fishes are some of the great utility spells. Each has a cost that, in proportion to their ability, is quite efficient. Shockwave and Undertow can remove a 1 energy creature just the same as a 15 energy creature. Blowing away the largest unprotected creature on the board can be the most fun of the game and even greater for the rest of the game.  Thunderquake is a variable spell that is a one size fits all card. If you need to remove 3 energy from the board and don&#8217;t want to waste a shockwave, then thunderquake is the answer. If it is 1 to 10 energy then thunderquake is a solution. Storm of Fishes is a variable mass removal card. It allows a selection of removing all spells from all players&#8217; hands or relics for under 4 energy.<br>
        There is also a new form of evolving utility. These are the metagame utility cards. Since the release of Dream&#8217;s End a set of relics have become something of an enigma. They are a small segment of the set that has been fitted to deal with the problems of discard. Abraxin&#8217;s Crown, Climbing Staff, and Tomorrow&#8217;s Jewel are just a few. They are utility but only when there is a discard heavy environment. So they can be added or ignored. Since they conform to metagame they are metagame utility. <br>
All of these are the more universal segment of utility. Each can make a deck whole in its strategy or fill a hole in the deck slot after the necessities are taken care of.  There is one more segment of utility that is often not taken as it is. These are the rest of the sets. Each region has utility that is select to its own region or to narrowly defined regions. Cataclysm is a good example. Its ability is amazing and the fact that it is a spell makes it more potent, but it is select to Core and Arderial. This makes it utility to only Core and Arderial. Each region has examples and the list is as long as there are cards.<br>
        One item is left to know about utility. It is only as good as the player using it, the flip side of the coin if you will. A Rayje&#8217;s Belt will only work if used the right way. Shockwave will only help you if you make it efficient.  Cards don&#8217;t play themselves. It is the style and flare of the player that brings out the real power of will needed to be good. It is a bit metaphysical but only a finely tuned deck select to its owner can be the best of the best. Once you take away the personality of a deck, there are only small pieces of card stock with pictures and words. Remember that little bit of personality you put into every card. Make the deck your own, a balance of power and finesse and fun.<br>
<br>
         Make utility your own.<br>
